Why is there no explicit topic hierarchy?
We began modeling such a hierarchy. But when thinking about how this structure could be mapped to the topic namespace and topic set defined in WS-Topics we recognized that we would break the modeling approach suggested there. In addition the approach from WS-Notification is not that difficult to understand - the subtleties of the WS-N specs only need to be explained more clearly.
We also promote the reuse of existing interfaces and data types.

UML:TaggedValue.value:
1) producerEndpoint property is mandatory, so each service shall indicate where clients need to send subscription requests to.
2) topicSet property is required for all services that allow subscribing to notifications.
3) fixedTopicSet: service needs to identify whether the topic set is fixed or not.
4,5,6) Dialects are required to indicate which filter functionality a service supports. Filters can be applied when subscribing for specific notifications. Not every dialect may be applicable to each topic. This could be indicated by adding topic metadata (in the topic namespace and/or topic set; in the former this could be a metdatada element added to the documentation element, while in the latter case it could be an attribute that lists the dialect URIs).
DO WE WANT TO DEFINE SUCH METADATA ELEMENTS?
7) A specific service instance can define its own custom topic namespace if it wishes to do so. In that case, it shall provide the topic namespace definition in its capabilities.
We could also add a list of URLs to the topic namespaces used inside an attribute of the service's TopicSet.
